The paper focuses on the early phase of neural network training, which is a topic that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The paper also discusses the emergence of sparse sub-networks and the importance of the dataset, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Additionally, the use of blurred inputs and self-supervised tasks suggests that the paper could be relevant to the cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-category. The paper's focus on supervised learning and the use of labels also suggests that it could be relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper's discussion of the weight distribution and its reliance on various aspects of the dataset suggests that it could be relevant to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category, which includes topics related to natural language processing and machine learning.
